{
  "doc_id": "11523",
  "text": "One of the parameters that strongly affect the metal removal capacity as well as the general position of the breakthrough curve is the initial metal ion concentration. According to the obtained results the uptake capacity increases as the inlet Mo (VI) concentration due to the increasing of driving force for mass transfer. This result is in agreement with that reported by Vijayaraghavan et al. [36,37], Han et al. [CITATION_1] and Malkoc et al. [CITATION_2] studies. On the other hand, the percentage of Mo (VI) removal decreases as the influent concentration of Mo (VI) increases because, when the column gets close to saturation, the quantity of metal biosorbed is very low in comparison to the quantity of metal that passes through the column. A similar trend was also observed for Cr (III) biosorption by olive stone [CITATION_3] .",
